# Clean Architecture + SOLID (required for new changes)

All new changes and implementations must follow **Clean Architecture** concepts and **SOLID** principles to maximize readability, extensibility, and maintainability.

## Clean Architecture checklist

- **Separate concerns**: keep business rules independent from frameworks/UI/IO.
- **Dependency direction**: dependencies must point inward (outer layers depend on inner layers, never the reverse).
- **Boundaries**: define clear interfaces/ports at boundaries (e.g., repositories, gateways, services).
- **Use cases**: organize application behavior around use-cases (what the app does) rather than technical details.
- **Frameworks as details**: treat web frameworks, DB clients, queues, etc. as replaceable adapters.

## SOLID checklist

- **S (SRP)**: each module/class/function has one reason to change.
- **O (OCP)**: extend behavior via composition/polymorphism/configuration instead of modifying core logic.
- **L (LSP)**: subtypes must be safely substitutable for their base types/contracts.
- **I (ISP)**: prefer small, specific interfaces over large “god” interfaces.
- **D (DIP)**: depend on abstractions; inject concrete implementations at the edges.

## Implementation expectations

- Prefer **composition** over inheritance.
- Keep domain/use-case code **free of side effects**; isolate IO at the edges.
- When adding a new dependency, introduce it behind an **interface** and provide an adapter implementation.

